{"title_page": "When the Pawn...", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = When the Pawn\u2026\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| cover        = Fiona apple when the pawn.jpg\n| alt          =\n| released     = November 9, 1999\n| recorded     = 1998\u20131999\n| venue        =\n| studio       = {{collapsible list|title=Various|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:12px;background:transparent;text-align:left|{{plainlist|\n* Andora Studio\n* Chateau Brion Studio\n* [[NRG Recording Studios]]\n* Ocean Way Studio\n* One On One South\n* Presence Studios\n* Woodwinds\n}}\n}}\n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Art pop]]|[[jazz]]|[[Rock music|rock]]}}\n| length       = 42:39\n| label        = Clean Slate/[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer     = [[Jon Brion]]\n| prev_title   = [[Tidal (album)|Tidal]]\n| prev_year    = 1996\n| next_title   = [[Extraordinary Machine]]\n| next_year    = 2005\n| misc         = {{singles\n | name        = When the Pawn Hits...\n | type        = album\n | single1     = [[Fast as You Can]]\n | single1date = November 20, 1999\n | single2     = Limp\n | single2date = 2000\n | single3     = [[Paper Bag (song)|Paper Bag]]\n | single3date = November 21, 2000\n}}\n}}\n'''''When the Pawn Hits the Conflicts He Thinks Like a King What He Knows Throws the Blows When He Goes to the Fight and He'll Win the Whole Thing 'fore He Enters the Ring There's No Body to Batter When Your Mind Is Your Might So When You Go Solo, You Hold Your Own Hand and Remember That Depth Is the Greatest of Heights and If You Know Where You Stand, Then You Know Where to Land and If You Fall It Won't Matter, Cuz You'll Know That You're Right''''', frequently abridged to '''''When the Pawn...''''', is the second studio [[album]] by American singer-songwriter [[Fiona Apple]].<ref name=\"Eliscu\">{{cite book |author=Eliscu, Jenny |editor1=Brackett, Nathan |editor2=Hoard, Christian D. |title=[[The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |date=2004 |publisher=Fireside |location=New York |isbn=0-74-320169-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/23 23] |edition=4th |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_New_Rolling_Stone_Album_Guide.html?id=t9eocwUfoSoC&q=%22when+the+pawn%22 |chapter=Fiona Apple }}</ref> Released by [[Epic Records]] in the United States on November 9, 1999, ''When the Pawn...'' was wholly written by Apple, with production by [[Jon Brion]].\n\nIn 2010, ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine named the album the 106th greatest of the last 25 years,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/spin25/125-best-albums-past-25-years#page=2 |title=125 Best Albums of the Past 25 Years|work=Spin|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' named it the 79th best album of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slantmagazine.com/music/feature/best-albums-of-the-90s/251/page_3 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218173858/http://slantmagazine.com/music/feature/best-albums-of-the-90s/251/page_3|archivedate=2011-02-18|title=Best Albums of the '90s|date=February 14, 2011|url-status=dead|access-date=2011-05-06}}</ref> The album received a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Album]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/fiona-apple |title=Fiona Apple|date=2018-05-22|work=GRAMMY.com|access-date=2018-06-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Title==\nThe album's title is a poem Apple wrote in response to unfavorable reactions from readers of an unfavorable ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine cover story about her.<ref name=\"Harrington\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/1999-11/28/003r-112899-idx.html |title=Fiona Apple: The Time Is Ripe |last=Harrington |first=Richard |date=November 28, 1999 |work=The Washington Post |page=G1}}</ref> Richard Harrington of ''The Washington Post'' called it Apple's version of [[Chumbawamba]]'s \"[[Tubthumping|I get knocked down, but I get up again]]\".{{r|Harrington}} \"It came from being made fun of,\" she said, \"and then, of course, it becomes a thing I'm being made fun of for.\"<ref>Sutcliffe, Phil, \"Hard Core Pawn\", ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'', March 2000, pp. 46-48</ref>\n\nUpon its release, ''When the Pawn...'' broke the record for longest album title at 444 characters (previously held by a volume in ''[[The Best... Album in the World...Ever!]]'').<ref>{{cite book|title=This Day in Music: An Every Day Record of Musical Feats and Facts: An Every Day Record of Musical Feats and Facts|last=Cossar|first=Neil|year=2010|publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=978-0-857-12362-6|p=395}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2014/06/guinness-book-of-world-records-music/worlds-longest-album-title|title=12 Guinness World Records That Exist For No Real ReasonWorld's Longest Album Title|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref> Chumbawamba themselves would end up breaking the record with 2008's ''[[The Boy Bands Have Won]]'', whose full title contains 865 characters, nearly twice as many as ''When the Pawn''...'s.  The album was produced and mixed by [[Jon Brion]] and co-mixed and engineered by [[Rich Costey]].\n\nThe full title is:\n{{Quote|When the pawn hits the conflicts he thinks like a king{{Break}}What he knows throws the blows when he goes to the fight{{Break}}And he'll win the whole thing 'fore he enters the ring{{Break}}There's nobody to batter when your mind is your might{{Break}}So when you go solo you hold your own hand{{Break}}And remember that depth is the greatest of heights{{Break}}And if you know where you stand then you know where to land{{Break}}And if you fall it won't matter 'cause you'll know that you're right}}\n\n==Release==\nThe first single, \"[[Fast as You Can]]\", was fairly popular and received moderate radio and [[music video|video]] airplay. It reached the top 20 on the US ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart and became Apple's first top 40 hit on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. The follow-up singles, \"Limp\" and especially \"[[Paper Bag (song)|Paper Bag]]\", which was nominated for a Grammy Award, were less successful. Apple's boyfriend at the time, filmmaker [[Paul Thomas Anderson]], directed videos for all three singles.{{citation needed|date=June 2018|reason=Full paragraph}}\n\nIn 2019, Apple collaborated with [[King Princess]] on a cover of \"I Know\". The song was released for Spotify's RISE program on January 25.<ref>https://www.npr.org/2019/01/25/688618778/king-princess-and-fiona-apple-collaborate-on-new-version-of-i-know?t=1548436537592</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 79/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/when-the-pawn/fiona-apple |title=Reviews for When The Pawn... by Fiona Apple |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=April 6, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-the-pawn-hits-the-conflicts-he-thinks-like-a-king-mw0000035134 |title=When the Pawn Hits the Conflicts He Thinks Like a King... \u2013 Fiona Apple |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4514532.html |title=Fiona Apple, 'When the Pawn . . .' (Clean Slate/Epic) |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=November 14, 1999 |accessdate=October 17, 2016 |last=Reed |first=Bobby |url-access=subscription |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118101527/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4514532.html |archivedate=November 18, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3score = A<ref name=browne>{{cite journal |url=https://www.ew.com/article/1999/11/12/when-pawn |title=When the Pawn... |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=November 12, 1999 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |last=Browne |first=David |authorlink=David Browne (journalist)}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1999/nov/09/entertainment/ca-31465 |title=Assured Apple Challenges Her Audience |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 9, 1999 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |last=Gardner |first=Elysa}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5score = 5/10<ref name=nme>{{cite journal |url=https://www.nme.com:80/reviews/reviews/20000315080021.html |title=Fiona Apple \u2013 When The Pawn... |work=[[NME]] |date=March 15, 2000 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |last=Martin |first=Piers |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000604111619/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/20000315080021.html |archivedate=June 4, 2000 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6score = 9.4/10<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/fiona-apple-when-the-pawn/ |title=Fiona Apple: When the Pawn... |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=March 24, 2019 |accessdate=March 24, 2019 |last=Berman |first=Judy}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.qonline.co.uk:80/reviews/server.asp?id=18741 |title=Fiona Apple: When The Pawn Hits The Conflicts... |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=162 |date=March 2000 |accessdate=August 30, 2018 |last=Aizlewood |first=John |page=101 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001121083400/http://www.qonline.co.uk/reviews/server.asp?id=18741 |archivedate=November 21, 2000 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Sheffield\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/when-the-pawn-hits-the-conflicts-he-thinks-like-a-king-19991125 |title=When the Pawn Hits the Conflicts He Thinks Like a King... |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=November 25, 1999 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Sheffield}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HJbW_6l-uRUC&pg=PT2&lpg=PT2 |title=Fiona Apple: When the Pawn Hits the Conflicts He Thinks Like a King / What He Knows Throws the Blows When He Goes to the Fight... |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=15 |issue=12 |date=December 1999 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |last=Weisbard |first=Eric |page=215}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv200-00.php |title=Consumer Guide: Cleanup Time |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=March 7, 2000 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n}}\n\nIn comparison to Apple's debut album ''[[Tidal (album)|Tidal]]'', Harrington stated, \"''When the Pawn'' is a decidedly more mature work that trades in youthful melodrama for somber ruminations on shattered relationships and romantic obsession\".{{r|Harrington}} In ''The New Rolling Stone Album Guide'', [[Jenny Eliscu]] states that ''Pawn'' is \"more musically complex and melodically advanced\" than the previous album, while focusing on Apple's \"sultry voice and moody piano playing\".{{r|Eliscu}} [[Rob Sheffield]] of ''Rolling Stone'' gave the album three-and-a-half out of five stars, calling it \"richer, deeper and stronger than ''Tidal'', in every way\", with \"a far more muscular approach to both the songs and the singing\".{{r|Sheffield}} ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] awarded the album an A grade, praising Jon Brion's production as well as Apple's songwriting: \"Apple hasn\u2019t gained much in psychic confidence following the success of ''Tidal''. On ''When the Pawn...'', Apple presents herself as a mental shambles, and she\u2019s more than happy to tell us about it.\"<ref name=browne/> ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' rated the album eight out of ten stars, with reviewer Chip Chanko praising Apple's lyrics, writing: \"[Apple] seems older. Her voice is full of a heartfelt soul that seems almost timeless. While [[Billie Holiday]] would never have considered the possibility of lines like, 'It won't be long till you'll be/ Lying limp in your own hand,' Apple executes them flawlessly with a modern passion.<ref name=chanko>{{cite web |url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/15003-when-the-pawn |title=Fiona Apple: When the Pawn... |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=January 21, 2016 |last=Chanko |first=Chip |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070611015221/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/15003-when-the-pawn |archivedate=June 11, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Amy Linden of ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' wrote: \"''When the Pawn...'' is full of images that resonate. Apple's a sad, sultry woman with a sense of who she is\u2014even if that person isn't someone she wants to be. Once again, her pain brings us joy.\"<ref>{{cite journal|work=Vibe|author=Linden, Amy|date=December 1999|p=257|volume=7|number=10|title=Fiona Apple - 'When the Pawn...'|issn=1070-4701}}</ref> Piers Martin of ''[[NME]]'' rated it a 5 out of 10, calling it Apple's \"second album of [[Tori Amos|Amos]]-aping MTV-branded Lilith Fair fodder.\"<ref name=nme/>\n\nAs of 2005, sales of the album in the United States had exceeded 922,000 copies, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref name=\"books.google.hr\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.hr/books?id=7hUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=fiona+apple+when+the+pawn+billboard&source=bl&ots=dd63BWNa-5&sig=Eg5V_0zYGZdjXiZXtHPrA0PtAMI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVuMXY7ZHYAhWHKewKHaHPBtIQ6AEIeTAM#v=onepage&q=fiona+apple+when+the+pawn+billboard&f=false|title=Billboard|first=Nielsen Business Media|last=Inc|date=8 October 2005|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|via=Google Books}}</ref> On March 26, 2020, ''When the Pawn..'' was certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Gold & Platinum - Fiona Apple |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=fiona+apple#search_section |website=riaa.com |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Fiona Apple]], except where noted\n| title1          = On the Bound\n| length1         = 5:22\n| title2          = To Your Love\n| length2         = 3:40\n| title3          = Limp\n| length3         = 3:29\n| title4          = Love Ridden\n| length4         = 3:22\n| title5          = [[Paper Bag (song)|Paper Bag]]\n| length5         = 3:39\n| title6          = A Mistake\n| length6         = 4:56\n| title7          = [[Fast as You Can]]\n| length7         = 4:38\n| title8          = The Way Things Are\n| length8         = 4:16\n| title9          = Get Gone\n| length9         = 4:07\n| title10         = I Know\n| length10        = 4:55\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Japanese edition bonus tracks\n| title11         = [[Across the Universe]]\n| note11          = [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n| length11        = 5:11\n| title12         = Never Is a Promise\n| note12          = Live\n| length12        = 6:12\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Fiona Apple \u2013 [[piano]], [[Singing|vocals]], synthesized bass {{small|(track 7)}}\n* [[Jon Brion]] \u2013 bass, keyboards, vibraphone, guitars, drums, percussion\n* John Bainbridge \u2013 orchestration\n* Robert Becker \u2013 [[viola]]\n* [[Charlie Bisharat]] \u2013 [[violin]]\n* Mike Breaux \u2013 woodwind\n* Denyse Buffman \u2013 viola\n* [[Jonathan \"Butch\" Norton]] \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], [[percussion instrument|percussion]]\n* Eve Butler \u2013 violin\n* [[Matt Chamberlain]] \u2013 percussion, drums\n* Susan Chatman \u2013 violin\n* [[Greg Cohen]] \u2013 [[bass guitar]]\n* Larry Corbett \u2013 [[cello]]\n* [[Mike Elizondo]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* Armen Garabedian \u2013 violin\n* Berj Garabedian \u2013 violi